```rust
struct FPSCounter {
    frame_counter: u32,
}

impl FPSCounter {
    fn new() -> Self {
        FPSCounter { frame_counter: 0 }
    }

    fn update(&mut self, frame_count: u32) {
        self.frame_counter += frame_count;
    }

    fn calculate_average_fps(&self, frame_counts: &Vec<u32>, time_period_seconds: u32) -> f32 {
        let total_frames: u32 = frame_counts.iter().sum();
        let average_fps = total_frames as f32 / time_period_seconds as f32;
        average_fps
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut fps_counter = FPSCounter::new();
    // Simulate frame updates
    fps_counter.update(60); // 60 frames rendered
    fps_counter.update(30); // 30 frames rendered
    fps_counter.update(45); // 45 frames rendered
    let frame_counts = vec![60, 30, 45];
    let time_period_seconds = 5;
    let average_fps = fps_counter.calculate_average_fps(&frame_counts, time_period_seconds);
    println!("Average FPS over {} seconds: {:.2}", time_period_seconds, average_fps);
}
```

In this solution, the `calculate_average_fps` function calculates the total frames rendered over the given time period by summing the frame counts in the input vector. Then, it divides the total frames by the time period in seconds to obtain the average FPS. Finally, the main function demonstrates the usage of the FPSCounter and prints the average FPS over the specified time period.

